INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3000','letter','1777-01-04','Peekskill','NY','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have just arrived here; find only part of two regiments of the militia, from the Massachusetts. The badness of the roads hath much retarded the troops.','ltr_bel3000.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3001','letter','1777-08-12','Stillwater','NY','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I waited upon General Schuyler, on my way to the militia who had assembled and were assembling at Manchester, on the Grants, received his instructions, and met the troops the 2d instant.','ltr_bel3001.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3201','letter','1778-03-17','Hingham','','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','Would not an early attempt upon the city of New York, by part of the Continental troops and the eastern militia, be attended with great probability of success ?','ltr_bel3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3202','letter','1778-06-01','Worcester','MA','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I was honored with your kind favor of the 7th ultimo, on the 19th, accompanying your valuable present, the epaulettes and sword-knot. ','ltr_bel3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3203','letter','1778-12-19','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','The troops have been supplied by this State ; and the heads of the several departments of Medical, Commissary, and Quarter-master, when supplies were necessary, have applied to the civil authority','ltr_bel3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3204','letter','1779-01-05','Purysburg','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','On the evening of the 25th ultimo, I received information at Charleston, that the enemy had arrived, with upwards of twenty ships, at Tybee, near the mouth of the River Savannah, and in a harbour south of the river.','ltr_bel3204.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3205','letter','1779-11-07','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','We remain unsupported by troops, unsupplied with many essential articles, and uncovered with works ; and, what adds to the unhappiness, is the little prospect that our affairs will speedily be in a better channel.','ltr_bel3205.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3206','letter','1780-01-08','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I hear, but have no official notice of it, that the Virginia line are ordered from the main army, to reenforce this department. If this should prove true, it will be fortunate indeed for this country','ltr_bel3206.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3207','letter','1780-01-23','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I had, a few days since, the honor of your favor of the 12th ultimo, by Colonel Laurens, announcing that the Virginia line were ordered to this department, than which nothing could be more acceptable, saving that of their not being needed.','ltr_bel3207.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3208','letter','1780-02-12','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have received information that, on the 3d instant, the enemy landed about eight thousand troops, commanded by Sir Henry Clinton.','ltr_bel3208.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3209','letter','1780-03-04','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','Sir Harry seems to be collecting his force on James\'s Island, and is there throwing up some works ; one among the ruins of Fort Johnson, another a little to the westward of it.','ltr_bel3209.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3210','letter','1780-03-24','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','Since my last, the enemy have, very unexpectedly, brought over the ships mentioned in the inclosed paper. It has been thought there was not water enough for a sixty-four gun ship.','ltr_bel3210.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3211','letter','1780-04-09','Charleston','SC','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','George','Washington','','individual','','The enemy crossed the Ashley, in force, near the ferry, on the 29th ultimo, and the next day moved down, and encamped about three thousand .yards from our lines.','ltr_bel3211.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3212','letter','1777-08-10','Bennington','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','','','','group','The Council Of Massachusetts','I find the men sent here from the county of Worcester, under the command of Colonel Gushing, left their homes in such haste, that they are by no means prepared to remain in camp any considerable time','ltr_bel3212.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3213','letter','1777-08-25','Bennington','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','','','','group','The Council Of Massachusetts','I hear that to-morrow I may expect five companies of the three months men. As soon as they arrive, I shall discharge the whole of Colonel Cushing\'s ; for the discontent among them is so general that they will be of very little service here','ltr_bel3213.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3214','letter','1777-09-04','Bennington','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','Horatio','Gates','','individual','','The person I sent to General Burgoyne is returned. He had an opportunity to confer with him, with Fraser and others, and was suffered to return into the country, under the character of a Recruiting Officer. ','ltr_bel3214.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3215','letter','1777-09-11','Pawlet','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','Horatio','Gates','','individual','','I should not have been short of ammunition, had the militia from the Massachusetts attended to the orders of the Court, and had the ball sent from Springfield and Albany been of a size suitable for the muskets.','ltr_bel3215.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3216','letter','1777-09-12','Pawlet','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','RECIPIENT FIRST','Brown','','individual','','You will please to take the command of five hundred men, and proceed, in the best route, to cross the Narrows, as soon as may be, to the landing at the north end of Lake George','ltr_bel3216.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3217','letter','1777-09-04','Pawlet','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','Horatio','Gates','','individual','','By a scout, who has been near Fort Edward, and from one of the inhabitants in that neighbourhood, I have a confirmation of the enemy\'s movements mentioned in your letter. I think it is not probable that their design is on your post.','ltr_bel3217.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3218','letter','1777-09-21','Pawlet','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','RECIPIENT FIRST','Brown','','individual','','All your movements since you left this place have [been] very agreeable to me. I am greatly obliged to you for your exertions, and am glad to hear, that with spirit the officers and men under you have distinguished themselves.','ltr_bel3218.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3219','letter','1777-09-23','','VT','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','','','','group','The Council Of Massachusetts','The success Colonel Brown hath met with, you learn by the inclosed, which is a copy of his letter to me. He hath acted with great spirit, and informs me that his officers and men have behaved with bravery. ','ltr_bel3219.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_bel3220','letter','1781-02-05','Boston','STATE','US','Benjamin','Lincoln','','John','Laurens','','individual','','n compliance with your wish, that I would give you the outlines of the several movements I made in the Northern department, in the year 1777, after General Gates reassumed the command, to my being wounded on the 8th of October, I offer the following short state of the matter.','ltr_bel3220.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
